HAving already finihed the firt Part of my Dicoure, which treats of the Upper Parts, let me in this bring in an Anatomical Dicoure of this middle Region of Life, and that with a more chearful pirit, by how much it is more noble and excellent than the former. For as Comographers do in a mall Map comprehend the Circuits, Regions, Ilands, Promontories, Fields and Valleys of the World, o may we in this our econd Dicoure, comprehend the Greatnes, Structure, Site, Figure, and all exteriour and interiour Parts, contained and containing in this Region, the which Region doth come under the Name of Thorax; o called either < in non-Latin alphabet > , which is Salio, the Heart herein being always in a leaping motion; or as the Stoicks affirm it, < in non-Latin alphabet > , Quod mentem Divinam animi partem denotat. This decribeth the whole Trunk of the Body, and whatoever is extended from the Jugulars to the Xyphoidal Cartilage and Diaphragma, comes under the Name of the Thorax. It is circumcribed in its upper parts with Clavicles, in its lower part with a Diaphragma, in its fore-part with a Sternon, in its back-part with the Vertebres of the Back, in its right and left ide with 12 Ribs. Its Figure is beautiful and capacious, partly boney, partly flehy; boney, for the trengthening of its mot noble veel the Heart; flehy, for the more eaie motion of its Diatole and Sytole. It obtains a Cavity between the upper and lower middle Region, for the more equal diffuion of its native heat into all the imple parts. It's framed of parts containing and contained;
the containing parts are ome of them Proper, others Common: The Common are 5, Cuticula, Cutis, Membrana Carnoa, Adeps, and Nervous Panniculus. The Proper are brought under thee 3 heads or ditinctions, as ome being oft and flehy, others boney and Cartilaginous, and the third Membranous. In this are locked up the vital Intruments and Wheels of Life, the rare Organs of Muick, whereby the Voice is o diverified, called by Hippocrates
< in non-Latin alphabet > , a Cittern, making here its Muick. Here may we ee the Heart diplay and communicate its vital pirits; how thee do quicken and trengthen the natural heat of the whole Body; how the Lungs as freh Fans do cool its heat, and by their motions as Bellows blow it up again, if occaion requires.
